---
import PageLayout from '../../layouts/PageLayout.astro';
import PhotoLightbox from '../../components/react/PhotoLightbox';
---

<PageLayout
  title="Origin: Hall C"
  description="A typing class, a green monochrome monitor, and a move to Texas — the earliest chapter of the story."
>
  <a
    href="/career"
    class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 text-sm font-medium text-orange-700 dark:text-orange-400 hover:underline mb-8"
  >
    ← Back to My Career
  </a>

  <header class="mb-8">
    <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-300 mb-1">
      Chapter
    </p>
    <h1 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight text-neutral-900 dark:text-neutral-100">
      Origin: Hall C
    </h1>
  </header>

  <div class="not-prose mb-8 relative overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-neutral-700 bg-black p-4 shadow-inner">
    <div
      class="pointer-events-none absolute inset-0 opacity-20"
      style="background-image: repeating-linear-gradient(to bottom, transparent 0, transparent 1px, #000 2px, #000 3px);"
    >
    </div>
    <div
      class="relative font-mono text-sm tracking-widest text-green-400 space-y-4"
      style="text-shadow: 0 0 5px rgba(74, 222, 128, 0.8), 0 0 10px rgba(74, 222, 128, 0.4);"
    >
      <p>]<span class="animate-pulse">▊</span></p>
      <p>]gggggggg hhhhhhhh a;sldkfjgh ghghghgh<span class="animate-pulse">▊</span></p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="prose prose-neutral dark:prose-invert max-w-none prose-a:text-brand-600 dark:prose-a:text-brand-300 prose-blockquote:border-brand-300 dark:prose-blockquote:border-brand-700 prose-code:font-mono prose-code:before:content-none prose-code:after:content-none">
    <p>
      In middle school, my father signed me up for a typing class as one of my
      electives. I threw quite the hissy fit about it. Why would I want to
      spend an entire class typing? It sounded unbelievably boring.
    </p>

    <p>
      The classroom was filled with <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apple_IIe" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Apple IIe</a> computers sporting green
      monochrome monitors and dual 5.25" <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Floppy_disk" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">floppy drives</a>. To this day, I can
      still remember the beep each computer made as it powered on, the feel
      and sound of those keyboards beneath my fingertips, and the endless
      rhythm of typing home row exercises.
    </p>

    <p>
      There's a reason people say, "fathers know best." As much as I hated
      that class at the time, I still type around 90 WPM today.
    </p>

    <p>It wasn't the only time he saw something I couldn't.</p>

    <p>
      Long before I understood what he was doing, he moved our family from
      Illinois to Texas. Looking back, I think he knew that neither of his
      sons was cut from the same farm-cloth as he was, or the generations
      before him. I hate the outdoors. Farming was never going to be my
      future.
    </p>

    <p>
      Instead, I started first grade in Allen, Texas, our new home.
    </p>

    <h2 id="finding-hall-c">Finding Hall C</h2>

    <figure class="not-prose float-right w-40 sm:w-56 ml-4 sm:ml-6 mb-4 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 dark:border-neutral-800 bg-neutral-50 dark:bg-neutral-900 p-2 shadow-sm">
      <PhotoLightbox
        src="/apple-iigs.jpg"
        alt="An Apple IIGS with keyboard, mouse, joystick, and external floppy drives"
        imgClass="w-full h-auto rounded-md"
        wrapperClass="block w-full rounded-md overflow-hidden"
        client:load
      />
      <figcaption class="mt-2 text-xs text-neutral-500 dark:text-neutral-400 text-center leading-snug">
        An Apple IIGS with keyboard, mouse, joystick, and external floppy drives
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Allen High School sat at the corner of Main St. and Jupiter Rd. As the
      number of students grew, so did the campus. The original section was on
      the south side, containing the main office and Halls A, B, and C. As the
      school expanded northward, it added Halls D and E, the cafeteria, the
      gymnasium, and finally the band hall and auditorium at the far north end
      of campus.
    </p>

    <p>
      Over the years, my mom would take me to school with her while she got
      some work done. Her room was unique. Part classroom and part office, it
      had a door leading into her private office in one corner. Next door was
      the Life Skills classroom, connected by an adjoining door. I still
      remember the covered parking spot next to the sidewalk and walking up
      the small ramp to the side entrance. I can still picture the layout of
      both rooms.
    </p>

    <p>
      I especially enjoyed getting to play on the Apple IIGS in her classroom.
      Compared to the Apple IIe computers I had used before, this one had a
      color monitor, a mouse, and actual sound through an external speaker. It
      felt incredibly advanced to me at the time. Looking back, I also realize
      what a blessing those computers were for the students in the Life Skills
      classroom.
    </p>

    <p>
      By the time I started my sophomore year, freshmen were still attending
      the middle school. My mom and I sat down to build my class schedule.
      Allen High had recently adopted block scheduling, which was still a
      fairly new concept in the late '90s.
    </p>

    <p>Band was already decided. That wasn't even a question.</p>

    <p>
      What about my other electives? Home Economics? Sports? Yeah, right.
      BCIS (Business Computer Information Systems)? I was already pretty
      advanced with Microsoft Office.
    </p>

    <p>I guess we'll sign up for... what's this? Computer Science?</p>

    <p>Uh, okay.</p>

    <p>
      I remember the first day of Computer Science. Most of my classes were
      on the north end of campus, so getting to Hall C was a bit of a trek. I
      can still smell the computers, the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cathode-ray_tube" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">CRT</a> monitors, the lockers, and
      whatever it was that made an old school smell like an old school.
    </p>

    <p>
      The classroom was split almost in half. On the left were the familiar
      rows of student desks. The right half of the room was lined with
      computers around three of the walls, waiting for us to sit down and see
      what they could do.
    </p>

    <p>The teacher, Coach Baker, seemed bigger than life.</p>

    <h2 id="coach-baker">Coach Baker</h2>

    <p>
      Sitting down at my desk and recognizing a few of the students around me,
      Coach Baker commanded the room. I couldn't tell if he was kind, grumpy,
      or somewhere in between. He spoke with authority, and all eyes were on
      him as he walked us through the syllabus.
    </p>

    <p>
      Somewhere in there, he talked about Alaska (was that where he was
      from?). He had graduated from Baylor in Waco and earned the title of
      "Coach" by leading the Allen High School lacrosse team (what a
      fascinating sport). Fortunately, the similarities between him and
      Trunchbull ended there.
    </p>

    <p>
      It didn't take long to realize he genuinely delighted in teaching young
      minds how to think thoughtfully, deeply, and well. He had this thing he
      did with his eyebrows, almost as if he were challenging you to stop and
      make sure you really believed what you had just said.
    </p>

    <p>
      That first year, we were introduced to the fundamentals of computer
      science: variables, constants, primitive data types, <code>if</code> statements,
      loops, <code>case</code> statements, arrays, and more. Our
      language of the year was <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turbo_Pascal" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Turbo Pascal 7</a>. Even today, I can picture the
      blue background, the simple menu bar across the top, and the yellow and
      white text that filled the screen.
    </p>

    <p>
      When it came time for tests, we had to write both code and pseudocode
      by hand. Coach Baker had a habit of giving "trick" tests to make sure we
      were paying attention. One simply instructed us to write our name at the
      top and turn it in.
    </p>

    <p>
      There was another lesson hidden in those tests. Your handwriting had to
      be legible. Mine wasn't.
    </p>

    <p>So I learned to write in small caps. Decades later, it's still my handwriting.</p>

    <p>
      When it came time to build my schedule for junior year, there really
      wasn't much of a decision to make. I signed up for Computer Science II.
      Not because I had discovered my future career. Far from it. If you had
      asked sixteen-year-old me what I wanted to do for a living, software
      engineer would not have even made the list. I loved Computer Science,
      and I thoroughly enjoyed Coach Baker's class, but I was convinced I
      never wanted to spend eight hours a day sitting behind a desk writing
      code.
    </p>

    <p>
      The truth was much simpler. I just wanted another year in Coach Baker's
      classroom.
    </p>

    <p>
      That year, we traded Turbo Pascal for a proprietary sprite-based
      programming language developed by <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/7th_Level" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">7th Level</a>, a game development company
      just a couple of towns away in Richardson. If memory serves, the
      language was called Studio 7, although I have never been able to find
      much information about it since. They had also created a game called <em><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G-Nome" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">G-NOME</a></em>,
      which had become fairly popular around North Texas.
      Naturally, we spent some class time playing it.
    </p>

    <p>
      Looking back, I appreciate what Coach Baker was doing. We were not just
      learning another programming language. He was showing us that software
      was something real people built. It was not confined to companies in
      California or names in the back of a textbook. There was a software
      company just down the road creating games, building tools, and making a
      living doing it.
    </p>

    <p>
      By senior year, there was never any question about my schedule.
      Computer Science III with Coach Baker was simply where I wanted to be.
      By then, there was a core group of us, the same students showing up
      year after year. It was always good to see familiar faces walk through
      the door on the first day of class. We already knew what to expect from
      Coach Baker, and he knew what to expect from us.
    </p>

    <p>
      This time, we graduated to <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Borland_C%2B%2B" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Borland C++</a>. The syntax changed. The compiler
      changed. The challenges grew a little more difficult. Somewhere along
      the way, I started noticing something that has stayed with me
      throughout my career.
    </p>

    <p>The language kept changing.</p>

    <p>The way you thought did not.</p>

    <h2 id="the-end-of-hall-c">The End of Hall C</h2>

    <p>
      I was in the last graduating class of that campus. The next year, a new
      building opened, and my mom, Coach Baker, and my other beloved teachers
      moved their classrooms there. The memories made in those halls didn't
      fade.
    </p>

    <p>
      Since my college was only twenty minutes away, I'd return frequently to
      visit my mom at school and swing by Coach Baker's classroom to see what
      he was teaching the next batch of students. I'd just sit with them as
      long as they'd let me. I didn't want to leave. Even today, Coach Baker
      is still teaching at another local school, helping students learn how
      to think.
    </p>

    <p>
      My high school was <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allen_High_School_(Texas)" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">demolished in 2018</a>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Hall C is gone. The band hall is gone. My mom's classroom in Hall D is
      gone. The halls where I learned to type, struggled through calculus,
      discovered programming, and spent countless hours are nothing more than
      memories now.
    </p>

    <p>But the building was never the important part.</p>

    <p>
      Turbo Pascal is gone. Borland C++ is gone. The proprietary language
      from 7th Level disappeared long ago. Even the Apple IIe and Apple IIGS
      that started it all belong in museums.
    </p>

    <p>
      Twenty-five years later, the tools have changed more times than I can
      count. Buildings have come and gone.
    </p>

    <p>What remained was learning how to think.</p>
  </div>
</PageLayout>
